text=!Generative models vs. Content Recognition%0aBy [[https://www.linkedin.com/in/carlo-andrea-trugenberger-92b190/ | Carlo Trugenberger, 26.1.2023]]%0a%0a[[https://books.google.com/talktobooks/query?q=Generative%2520language%2520models | '''Generative language models''']], like ChatGPT, are all the rage these days. These%0amodels are probability distributions over sequences of words. Given a sequence%0aof (n-1) words, the most likely next word is determined as the sequence of n%0awords with the highest probability, given the shorter sequence.%0a%0aTwo facts should immediately catch the eye. First, language models need%0aextensive training on a specific corpus before they can be used. Second, and%0arelated to this, they are not able to disambiguate. Once trained on a biology-%0afocused corpus, a language model will predict that Tiger should be followed by%0awords like species or endangered rather than Woods as would be more%0alikely for a sports-related document.%0a%0aLanguage models are prone to pique the interest of the wider public, given their%0ahuman-like abilities to answer questions and generate essays on the topics on%0awhich they have been trained. However, "The cost of training is the real%0abottleneck in the application of AI/NLP. Companies spend millions of dollars%0aweekly just to train and fine-tune their AI workloads," (Prof. A. Shrivastava,%0aRice University, Houston, April 2021). And, when questions outside the%0atraining domain of a language model, like ChatGPT, are asked, the answers are%0aimmediately very wrong, as was to be expected.%0a%0aTools like ChatGPT surely have many potential commercial applications, as the%0ainvestments of companies like Microsoft testify. One for which they are truly%0aunsuited, however is, e.g., creating summaries, especially of very long%0adocuments. As is very well explained on OpenAIs own Web site,%0ahttps://www.width.ai/post/gpt3-summarizer, there are two types of%0asummaries, extractive ones, in which exact sentences and keywords of the%0amain text are selected that represent best its overall content, and abstractive%0asummaries, in which the original text is supplanted by new, more compact%0asentences supposedly representing the same content. While abstractive%0asummaries might superficially seem more appealing, they are far too%0adangerous for productive applications. What is the use of a summarization%0atool you cannot trust 100%25?%0a%0aLanguage models use the fancy names zero-shot summarization or multiple-%0ashot summarization to refer to unsupervised summarization, that does not%0aneed training, or summarization algorithms that need training, in various%0apossible forms (see https://www.width.ai/post/gpt3-summarizer). But what is%0athe commercial use of a summarization tool that needs to be trained each time%0aon the very documents it should facilitate the comprehension of? Of course,%0aonly zero-shot summarization makes any sense! And, as it is clearly stated on%0athe above OpenAI page, zero-shot summarization with language models like%0a[[https://www.perplexity.ai/?uuid=a0c67efe-d892-488f-bd05-ad3c4266eb15 | GPT-3]] fails for long documents, as expected. This is particularly true for book-%0alength documents, for which language models like GPT-3 need constant human%0afeedback (https://openai.com/blog/summarizing-books/), a contradiction in%0aterms for productive applications in which humans know nothing about the text%0aand expect to actually gain knowledge from the AI tool! And documents this%0along are ubiquitous in several fields, like legal or medical expertises.%0a%0aUnsupervised summarization, even of very long documents, is the realm of%0a'''content-recognition AI''', a direction orthogonal to generative language models.%0aHere the focus is not on producing text but, rather, on the unsupervised%0aidentification of the meaning of existing text, '''with no training and on generic topics'''. %0aContrary to generative language models, this paradigm excels at%0asummarization, even of very long documents. It is also ideal to group and find%0adocuments by similarity and for knowledge discovery, the holy grail of text%0amining [[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3404399/ | (Hahn U, Cohen KB, Garten Y, Shah NH, Mining the pharmacogenomics literature: a survey of the state of the art. Brief Bioinform. 2012, 13(4):460494)]], which requires the ability to identify previously unnoticed, hidden%0acorrelations and is paramount for investigative and research work, e.g. for drug%0adiscovery.%0a%0aInfoCodex is such a content-recognition engine. It is based on probably the%0alargest linguistic database in the world, combined with information theory and%0aself-organizing neural networks. Its linguistic knowledge base is universal, it%0acovers generic topics and is organized hierarchically. This permits the%0ainformation theory algorithms to identify by themselves the relevant topics of%0aa document and to consequently automatically disambiguate possibly equivocal%0awords. Tiger will not be identified as an animal in a document about golf.%0aContext is paramount and training is not necessary, the tool trains itself. The%0aself-organizing neural networks will then provide the pattern recognition%0acapability to identify similarity of meaning, i.e. automatic content recognition%0awithout previous training and on generic topics.%0a%0a[[https://infocodex.com/ | InfoCodex]], contrary to GPT-3 or ChatGPT, can instantly provide summaries of%0atext of any length, even of entire books, on any topic and without previous%0atraining or human feedback. While generative models have surely a wealth of%0aapplications, they are clearly not ideal for summarization and knowledge%0adiscovery. For these crucial applications you need unsupervised content-%0arecognition, i.e. a tool like InfoCodex.%0a%0aFor a demo of InfoCodex please contact: zdavatz@ywesee.com
