diff:1674734539:1674734539:=1,81d0%0a%3c !Generative models vs. Content Recognition%0a%3c '''Generative language models''', like ChatGPT, are all the rage these days. These%0a%3c models are probability distributions over sequences of words. Given a sequence%0a%3c of (n-1) words, the most likely next word is determined as the sequence of n%0a%3c words with the highest probability, given the shorter sequence.%0a%3c %0a%3c Two facts should immediately catch the eye. First, language models need%0a%3c extensive training on a specific corpus before they can be used. Second, and%0a%3c related to this, they are not able to disambiguate. Once trained on a biology-%0a%3c focused corpus, a language model will predict that Tiger should be followed by%0a%3c words like species or endangered rather than Woods as would be more%0a%3c likely for a sports-related document.%0a%3c %0a%3c Language models are prone to pique the interest of the wider public, given their%0a%3c human-like abilities to answer questions and generate essays on the topics on%0a%3c which they have been trained. However, "The cost of training is the real%0a%3c bottleneck in the application of AI/NLP. Companies spend millions of dollars%0a%3c weekly just to train and fine-tune their AI workloads," (Prof. A. Shrivastava,%0a%3c Rice University, Houston, April 2021). And, when questions outside the%0a%3c training domain of a language model, like ChatGPT, are asked, the answers are%0a%3c immediately very wrong, as was to be expected.%0a%3c %0a%3c Tools like ChatGPT surely have many potential commercial applications, as the%0a%3c investments of companies like Microsoft testify. One for which they are truly%0a%3c unsuited, however is, e.g., creating summaries, especially of very long%0a%3c documents. As is very well explained on OpenAIs own Web site,%0a%3c https://www.width.ai/post/gpt3-summarizer, there are two types of%0a%3c summaries, extractive ones, in which exact sentences and keywords of the%0a%3c main text are selected that represent best its overall content, and abstractive%0a%3c summaries, in which the original text is supplanted by new, more compact%0a%3c sentences supposedly representing the same content. While abstractive%0a%3c summaries might superficially seem more appealing, they are far too%0a%3c dangerous for productive applications. What is the use of a summarization%0a%3c tool you cannot trust 100%25?%0a%3c %0a%3c Language models use the fancy names zero-shot summarization or multiple-%0a%3c shot summarization to refer to unsupervised summarization, that does not%0a%3c need training, or summarization algorithms that need training, in various%0a%3c possible forms (see https://www.width.ai/post/gpt3-summarizer). But what is%0a%3c the commercial use of a summarization tool that needs to be trained each time%0a%3c on the very documents it should facilitate the comprehension of? Of course,%0a%3c only zero-shot summarization makes any sense! And, as it is clearly stated on%0a%3c the above OpenAI page, zero-shot summarization with language models like%0a%3c GPT-3 fails for long documents, as expected. This is particularly true for book-%0a%3c length documents, for which language models like GPT-3 need constant human%0a%3c feedback (https://openai.com/blog/summarizing-books/), a contradiction in%0a%3c terms for productive applications in which humans know nothing about the text%0a%3c and expect to actually gain knowledge from the AI tool! And documents this%0a%3c long are ubiquitous in several fields, like legal or medical expertises.%0a%3c %0a%3c Unsupervised summarization, even of very long documents, is the realm of%0a%3c '''content-recognition AI''', a direction orthogonal to generative language models.%0a%3c Here the focus is not on producing text but, rather, on the unsupervised%0a%3c identification of the meaning of existing text, '''with no training and on generic%0a%3c topics'''. Contrary to generative language models, this paradigm excels at%0a%3c summarization, even of very long documents. It is also ideal to group and find%0a%3c documents by similarity and for knowledge discovery, the holy grail of text%0a%3c mining (Hahn U, Cohen KB, Garten Y, Shah NH, Mining the pharmacogenomics%0a%3c literature: a survey of the state of the art. Brief Bioinform. 2012, 13(4):460%0a%3c 494), which requires the ability to identify previously unnoticed, hidden%0a%3c correlations and is paramount for investigative and research work, e.g. for drug%0a%3c discovery.%0a%3c %0a%3c InfoCodex is such a content-recognition engine. It is based on probably the%0a%3c largest linguistic database in the world, combined with information theory and%0a%3c self-organizing neural networks. Its linguistic knowledge base is universal, it%0a%3c covers generic topics and is organized hierarchically. This permits the%0a%3c information theory algorithms to identify by themselves the relevant topics of%0a%3c a document and to consequently automatically disambiguate possibly equivocal%0a%3c words. Tiger will not be identified as an animal in a document about golf.%0a%3c Context is paramount and training is not necessary, the tool trains itself. The%0a%3c self-organizing neural networks will then provide the pattern recognition%0a%3c capability to identify similarity of meaning, i.e. automatic content recognition%0a%3c without previous training and on generic topics.%0a%3c %0a%3c InfoCodex, contrary to GPT-3 or ChatGPT, can instantly provide summaries of%0a%3c text of any length, even of entire books, on any topic and without previous%0a%3c training or human feedback. While generative models have surely a wealth of%0a%3c applications, they are clearly not ideal for summarization and knowledge%0a%3c discovery. For these crucial applications you need unsupervised content-%0a%3c recognition, i.e. a tool like InfoCodex.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
